<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Greenium</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine two slightly differe=
nt stories about environmental, social and governance-focused investing:</p=
><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;=
">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">ESG is about doing the most possible=
 good. ESG funds look to put their money into companies that do the best th=
ings for the environment, diligently researching the best and most innovati=
ve companies and investing in them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">ESG is about accommodating the most possible money. There is a gusher of =
money being invested in ESG funds, and the people managing those funds are =
looking to put the money into places with capacity for it.=C2=A0</li></ol><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So take green bonds, bonds that contain some pr=
omise to use the money for some environmental purpose. You might imagine th=
at the main issuers of green bonds would be relatively small companies focu=
sed on transformative clean-tech-type innovations, companies that can=E2=80=
=99t necessarily access the regular bond market but that can sell bonds to =
investors who care more about the environment than about profits.=C2=A0<em>=
Or </em>you might imagine that the main issuers of green bonds would be gia=
nt banks who issue lots of bonds to fund lots of different projects, and so=
me of those projects are green projects that the banks fund with green bond=
s, while other projects are dirty projects that the banks fund with regular=
 bonds. If you are a green-bond investor, which sort of issuer would you pr=
efer? Well, if you prefer doing maximum good, you might prefer the clean-te=
ch companies. If you prefer deploying maximum amounts of money, you might p=
refer the banks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a fun Federal Rese=
rve discussion paper on =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/28001654.264606/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L2Vj=
b25yZXMvaWZkcC90aGUtZ3JlZW4tY29ycG9yYXRlLWJvbmQtaXNzdWFuY2UtcHJlbWl1bS5odG0=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2ae249e3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">The Green Corporate Bond Issuan=
ce Premium</a>=E2=80=9D by John Caramichael and Andreas Rapp:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We study a global panel of green and convent=
ional bonds to assess the borrowing cost advantage at issuance for green bo=
nd issuers. We find that, on average, green bonds have a yield spread that =
is 8 basis points lower relative to conventional bonds. This borrowing cost=
 advantage, or greenium, emerges as of 2019 and coincides with the growth o=
f the sustainable asset management industry following EU regulation. Within=
 this context, we find that the greenium is linked to two proxies of demand=
 pressure, bond oversubscription and bond index inclusion. Moreover, while =
green bond governance appears to matter for the greenium, the credibility o=
f the underlying projects does not have a significant impact. Instead, the =
greenium is unevenly distributed to large, investment-grade issuers, primar=
ily within the banking sector and developed economies.</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The banks are where the money is, and also where t=
he greenium is. =E2=80=9CThe credibility of the underlying projects does no=
t have a significant impact,=E2=80=9D but being an investment-grade frequen=
t issuer whose bonds go into indexes does.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header"=
